<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>RW wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">His administration is gutting environmental policy.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
Between your few posts here on our little forum and on your blog you are very good at making accusations without actually providing any evidence.
<br />

<br />
As a former environmental chemist (1999-2003), I can tell you that the environmental rules are much stricter today than in the Clinton administration.  Some of it involves the analytical procedures.  More labs are now required to be <a href="http://www.epa.gov/nerlesd1/land-sci/nelac/index.html" target="_blank" class="postlink">NELAC</a> certified, which is basically a pain in the %@$# means to determine how well environmental anlysis are performed.
<br />
The talk about an incrase in mercury levels in soil is hogwash, or rather it was just talk.  The actual EPA methods and Code of Federal Regulations (40 CFR) were not changed.
<br />
If anything the reporting level of analytes decreased.  The reporting limit (along with method detection limit, instrument detection limit, etc) is the amount at which anything above can be reported as positive and anything below is reported negative or BDL (below detection limit).  So if the reporting limit decreased, that means a smaller value of analyte (e.g. benzene, PCBs, pesticides, Hg, etc) is being reported out; things are more sensitive.
<br />
Now, to be fair, it was not Bush that implemented in process improvement change.  Came from the EPA and each State.  It is one of the typical things where the presidential administration has little, if anything, to do with how environmental issues are handled in the real world.  On the other hand, Bush did not do anything to disrupt environmental policies.
<br />
It does get complicated because a lot of it falls under 40 CFR which is controlled by the US Congress but enforced and interpeted by the EPA.
<br />
But, what the hell do I know.  I just did it for a living.  I am sure that means nothing if it is not on some blog.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>RW wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> He refuses to make the oil drillers do anything about the thousands of seep ponds they leave that are breeding grounds for millions of mosquitos carrying West Nile Virus, further endangering the public health.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
