<br />

<br />
I design mutual funds for a living and we got all kinds of strategies which measure risk vs return. We factor in all kinds of stuff like interest rates, market inflows vs outflows,  core inflation, soft inflation, etc.. including the price of oil. Last time I checked we had 1.4 trillion dollars under our belt and owned 6% of everything listed on Nasdaq and NYSE outright. The mutual fund scandals as been a major boon to us this year since all our strategies are based on indexes and scientific formulas instead of individual stock picks.
<br />

<br />
I've been watching oil go up day by day for nine months now since it's my job and I've got all the individual daily reasons why oil is jumping stashed in the back of brain.
<br />

<br />
The Bush administration has done absolutely NOTHING to keep prices low.
<br />

<br />
There's so much more they can do..
<br />

<br />
1. I don't see them pushing OPEC to drill more barrels.
<br />
2. I don't see them pushing for conservation.
<br />
3. I don't see them offering advice to Russia in the Yukos mess (oil giant in russia) which is in financial trouble from owning back taxes. In the US we have something called chapter 11 which allows a company to continue to operate while they restructure. In Russia they are thinking about just pulling their oil drilling licenses.
<br />
4. I don't see US diplomats stepping in to help negotiate labor agreements in Venezuela and Nigeria. Oil workers are threatening to strike over low pay.
<br />
5. I don't see the Bush administration even mentioning the possiblity of opening up the strategic reserve. If this was a poker game they need to learn how to bluff to win sometimes.
<br />
6. I don't see them forcing oil companies to build new refinaries.
<br />
7. I don't see them telling oil companies they have to keep PROFITABLE refinaries open.
<br />
8. I don't see them promoting alternative energy development.
<br />

<br />
Everytime there is a price spike they just sit on the sidelines and watch.
<br />

<br />
Their energy policy is non-existant and it is killing our economy. If something isn't done soon I can almost guarantee that we will slip back into a recession next year. The signs are out there.
<br />

<br />
1. Leading indicators have dropped four months in a row. This hasn't happened since right after 9/11.
<br />

<br />
2. The fed is raising interest rates anticipating growth, but interest rates on bonds have dropped to a 6 month low. Demand for bonds is going way up which means there is little faith in the stock market  and our economy.
<br />

<br />
3. Job growth is anemic. Companies are not hiring enough workers each month to replace the ones leavings through ordinary retirement.
<br />

<br />
4. Price of oil and healthcare is skyrocketing which is sucking up any savings the middle class has and spending is what keeps the economy going.
<br />

<br />
I'm not pro-Kerry, but I am anti-Bush after watching this train wreck. Things at home are falling apart.
<br />

<br />
Right now I'm personally invested in overseas companies like China Petroleum and BHP, but I rather be shifting some of my assets back home into industries like biotech and hitech which improve our quality of living.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
