				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Nice article from the Institute for International Economics.
<br />

<br />
This pretty much sums everything I've been saying in one paragraph..
<br />

<br />
"The fifth threat is energy prices. In the short run, the rapid growth of world demand, low private inventories, shortages of refining and other infrastructure (particularly in America), continued American purchases for its strategic reserve and fears of supply disruptions have outstripped the possibilities for increased production. Hence prices have recently hit record highs in nominal terms. The impact is extremely significant since every sustained rise of $10 per barrel in the world price takes $250 billion to $300 billion (equivalent to about half a percentage point) off annual global growth for several years. Mr. Greenspan frequently notes that all three major postwar recessions have been triggered by sharp increases in the price of oil."
<br />

<br />
I would add that there is a sixth threat out there..
<br />

<br />
Which is a demographic shift in the USA of baby boomers which are moving out of the working population into the retirement population. There's gonna be a big sucking sound when millions of working tax payers turn the tables and start collecting social security and medicare benefits. A big federal budget deficit, lower government tax revenue and more government obligations in retiree benefit payments is unavoidable.
<br />

<br />
Unless the economy really picks up and starts generating tax revenue or we raise income taxes now we're going to be in major trouble. Kerry has already vowed not to raise taxes on the middle class so I just don't see how we can avoid the biggest financial crisis coming since the great depression.
<br />

<br />
I should just buy a nice tropical island and hide out for a couple decades.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
